> Problem Statement

Create an empty list lst = [] and perform a series of operations on it based on the commands provided.

The following commands are supported:

insert i e : Insert the integer e at index i.
print : Display the current contents of the list.
remove e : Remove the first occurrence of the integer e from the list.
append e : Add the integer e to the end of the list.
sort : Sort the list in ascending order.
pop : Remove the last element from the list.
reverse : Reverse the order of the elements in the list.

You are given an integer N, representing the number of commands to be executed. The next N lines each contain one command. Process the commands in the order they are given and perform the corresponding operation on the list.

For every print command, output the current state of the list.

Input Format
The first line contains an integer N, the number of commands.
The next N lines each contain a command.
Output Format
For each print command, print the list on a new line.
Example

Input

4
append 1
append 2
insert 1 3
print

Output

[1, 3, 2]


> Solution

if __name__ == '__main__':
    N = int(input())
    
    lt = []

for _ in range(N):
    
    command = input().split()
    
    if command[0] == "insert":
        
        lt.insert(int(command[1]),int(command[2]))
        
    elif command[0] =="print":
        
        print(lt)
        
    elif command[0] =="remove":
        
        lt.remove(int(command[1]))
        
    elif command[0] =="append":
        
        lt.append(int(command[1]))
        
    elif command[0] == "sort":
        
        lt.sort()
        
    elif command[0] == "pop":
        
        lt.pop()
        
    elif command[0] == "reverse":
        
        lt.reverse()
        
        
